// Fires when the parse queue consumer errors 2+ DISTINCT files within the last
// 15 minutes (malformed raw session file, unexpected harness format, etc — see
// hub/migrations/0001_init.sql's `parse_error` column, which M1's queue
// consumer is expected to also mirror into a structured console.log).
//
// Two noise guards, added 2026-07-23 after a lone transient D1 blip
// (`D1_ERROR: Network connection lost.`) paged at 01:40 UTC for a file that had
// already self-healed on the collector's next re-upload:
//   1. Transient D1 errors are EXCLUDED here. The consumer now retries these
//      instead of stamping a terminal parse.error (see consumer.ts
//      isTransientD1Error / TRANSIENT_D1_ERROR_SUBSTRINGS) — but this filter is
//      belt-and-braces: it keeps the alert quiet during the deploy window before
//      that code ships, and for any transient string not yet in the allowlist.
//   2. Threshold is 2+ DISTINCT files, not 2+ log rows. The consumer retries a
//      terminal failure up to the queue's max_retries (3) before DLQ, re-logging
//      parse.error on every delivery — so ONE persistent bad file emits several
//      rows. Counting rows would let a single one-off file trip a `> 1` guard;
//      dcount(file_id) makes the signal "multiple files failed", which a genuine
//      incident is (yesterday's migration-0013 schema break errored 4 files) and
//      a lone malformed file is not — that one surfaces in the fleet-health
//      files_error count / system-health workbook instead of paging. Keep both
//      filters in the query, not provision.sh: the shared `count 'Placeholder_1'
//      > 0` condition there is generic across all alerts, so the summarize +
//      threshold lives here and trips that > 0 on the single surviving row.
//
// See missed-heartbeat.kql for the OTelLogs/Body-as-JSON assumption this query
// shares. ASSUMPTION TO VERIFY AT M4 DEPLOY: confirm the table/column names
// once real data flows, and confirm the M1 parse consumer actually emits
// `{ event: "parse.error", ... }` (as opposed to only writing parse_error to D1
// without a matching structured log — if so, this alert needs a different
// signal, e.g. a scheduled query against D1 via a small status-reporting
// endpoint rather than Log Analytics).

// `otel` wraps OTelLogs in `union isfuzzy=true` so a missing table (before the
// first OTLP log lands) degrades to empty instead of erroring the whole rule —
// see missed-heartbeat.kql's "Missing-table guard" note for the full rationale.
let otel = union isfuzzy=true
    (datatable(TimeGenerated:datetime, Body:string)[]),
    (OTelLogs | project TimeGenerated, Body);
otel
| where TimeGenerated > ago(15m)
| extend body = todynamic(Body)
| where body.event == "parse.error"
| extend err = tostring(body.error), fid = tostring(body.file_id)
// Drop known-transient D1 blips — the consumer retries these; see header note 1.
// `contains` (substring), NOT `has`: `has` is term-based and won't reliably match
// these multi-word phrases, so a transient row could survive and page.
| where err !contains "Network connection lost"
    and err !contains "storage caused object to be reset"
    and err !contains "reset because its code was updated"
    and err !contains "Cannot resolve Durable Object"
// A bare summarize (no `by`) yields exactly one row — files counts DISTINCT
// affected file_ids (not rows: a retried terminal failure logs several), errors
// samples the messages for the notification. `where files > 1` emits that row
// only when 2+ files failed, so provision.sh's `count > 0` condition fires on a
// real multi-file incident, never on one retried one-off. See header note 2.
| summarize files = dcount(fid), errors = make_set(err, 10)
| where files > 1
| project files, errors
